 an hour. A small assembly sat on wooden seats, elevated from the crowd by a large platform. A half dome had been built around the platform, to focus the volume of the speakers to the people below. There, standing in the front of the mass, was a small form of neatly dressed cadets, the females wearing long, white silken dresses with blue ribbons tied around thier waist. The males were dressed less extravagant, wearing white silk jerkins and long blue breeches, but still retained the aura of purity and finesse.<br>
<br>
The city had been rebuilt over the past few months, and the High Elves had been recruiting hundreds of new, young males and females to fill the ranks of the lost. This was a glorious moment, as the first squad of youngsters was about to become true paladins.<br>
General Jyleel and two of his aides walked up to the front of the platform, Jyleel taking another step forward.<br>
&quot;People of Felwithe, Children of the Mother, friends and family members alike, we are here to witness the Mother's inception of new warriors, proud and true, into her ranks of worthy Paladins.&quot; he began.<br>
<br>
The speech droned on and on, and seemed to have no end.<br>
&quot;You know,&quot; Fenye muttered, &quot;I always thought that you could never kill a person with boredom. The fact that I am still here alive is a testament to that.&quot;<br>
The snickering of her nearby friends caught the eye of one of Jyleel's aide, who shot an icy glare to the young elves.<br>
<br>
Finally, it was time for the ceremony, and the bards of Kelethin began to play thier instruments with grace and fluidity. The young cadets began to file themselves up on the platform in a single file line, and one by one, they walked up to Jyleel. He raised his Holy Sword, and tapped each cadet on his or her shoulder, and said a prayer to Tunare, and with each cadet, the Divine Light of Tunare shone from the heavens to touch the young one, marking them as a Paladin from that day on.<br>
Now it was Fenye's turn. Nervous, she walked towards Jyleel, but his warm smile reassured herself that nothing would go wrong. But strangely, all the voices seemed to be dulled out, and his own words were uncomprehensable. Something was wrong. Something was very wrong.<br>
<br>
&quot;Fenye! Wake up!&quot; shouted one of her bunkmates from the academy. She had overslept again. The anxiety of gradutating was overwhelming, and she only had two weeks until it was time. But today was going to be like any other, just more vigorous training and mental games to keep the mind sharp.<br>
<br>
Running half dressed and unbathed to the fields, Fenye caught up with the rest of the troop. <br>
&quot;Today you will embark on your first mission. For each of you it will be different, and for each of you it will be a quest, a test of your worth. I will not see you again until it is time for you to graduate, and you will not graduate until your test is proven.<br>
&quot;I am also not going to tell you what your quest is. You will find it. If Tunare is truly with you, she will guide you to your quest.&quot; With a smile he turned his back, and headed into the barracks, leaving the cadets dumbfounded.<br>
Fenye stood there, rubbing her eyes in disbelief. But smiling, she knew she could (and probably should) rest a bit before opening her mind to let Tunare show her the path she was to follow.<br>
Crawling back into her soft hay mattress, she drifted off to sleep..<br>
<br>
